Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Sentencing – Sentencing approach for s 419 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed) involving a sex scam

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Sentencing – Sentencing approach for s 384 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed) involving a threat to post nude photographs on the Internet to induce the victim to send sexual photographs and video

16 November 2022 - Judgment reserved.

### District Judge Kow Keng Siong:

## Introduction

1       In _Wong Tian Jun De Beers v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGHC 273</span> (“**_Wong Tian Jun_**”), the High Court formulated a sentencing matrix for _s 417_ of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed) (“**the Penal Code**”). This matrix applies to offenders who have cheated their victims into providing “free” sexual acts and sexual images of themselves (“**sex scam**”). Is the sentencing matrix applicable to sex scam offenders convicted under _s 419_ of the Penal Code – and if so, how? This issue is raised in the present case.

2       The offender is Muhammad Nazri bin Sapar (“**the Accused**”). Arising from a series of sex scams that he had committed, the Accused faces a total of 46 charges for (a) cheating by personation, (b) extortion, (c) transmission of sexually explicit photographs and videos (“**sexual materials**”), (d) possession of obscene films and films without valid certification, (e) having procured a woman for the purpose of prostitution, and (f) voluntarily causing hurt. Save for the offence of voluntarily causing hurt, the rest of the offences were committed from 2014 to 2018 against five female victims.

3       The Accused has pleaded guilty to 15 charges and has consented to the remaining charges to be taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing. The proceeded charges are as follows:

## The facts

4       The Accused had used social media platforms to perpetuate his sex scams. According to the Statement of Facts to which he had admitted –

> 6 Sometime in 2014, the accused created an email account, XXX@hotmail.com. With this email, he created a Facebook account, which account name and profile picture was frequently changed. He would pick names belonging to female Malays such as “Shahirah Abbas”, “Shahirah Melak”, “Irah Chocopie” and “Nurul Huda”. He would also use pictures of female Malays obtained from the internet as his profile picture. This allowed him to easily approach female Malays without them being wary. If a female Malay rejected his friend request, he would change the account name and profile picture to approach the same female Malay. The accused was behind these fictitious characters.

5       The Accused’s sex scams only came to end when the Police managed to establish his identity and arrested him in May 2018.

### Facts relating to charges in \[3(1)\] – \[3(5)\]

6       The charges in \[3(1)\] – \[3(5)\] involve **Victim 1**. The Accused had admitted to the following facts relating to these charges:

> 7.    Sometime in November 2014, the accused used his Facebook account **_“Irah Chocopie”_** and added \[Victim 1\] on Facebook. In the course of their conversation over Facebook messenger, \[Victim 1\] confided in the accused and told him that she was in debt and needed money. The accused suggested that \[Victim 1\] work as a prostitute. He told her that one “Nurul Huda” will contact her.

> 8.    Posing as **_“Nurul Huda”_**, the accused contacted \[Victim 1\] over Whatsapp and told \[Victim 1\] that she (referring to “Nurul Huda”) is working as a prostitute under “Shahirah Abbas” (the boss of the purported prostitution ring) and “Hafiz” (the purported pimp of the purported prostitution ring). “Nurul Huda” shared her experience working as a prostitute with \[Victim 1\]. “Nurul Huda” also told \[Victim 1\] that in order to join the prostitution ring, she would have to send her nude photographs to “Hafiz” and “Hafiz” would have to try her services. “Nurul Huda” assured \[Victim 1\] that this was an industry norm that all new prostitutes had to undergo. \[Victim 1\] agreed to the conditions. \[Victim 1\] sent her nude photographs to “Hafiz”. She also met up with the accused posing as “Hafiz” and fellated him as she was deceived by the accused to believe that he was a pimp and that she had to do so, in order to join the prostitution ring. For the avoidance of doubt, there was no such prostitution ring.

> 9.    \[Victim 1\] subsequently joined the purported prostitution ring. The accused, under the guise of “Nurul Huda”, arranged two clients for her. Thereafter, the accused created a username “Lala” (referring to \[Victim 1\]) in “Alamak Chat” with the following autoreply “_if you wish to have sex services, please contact “Lala” at handphone…_”. From thereon, all subsequent clients contacted \[Victim 1\] directly through the “Alamak Chat” set up by the accused.

> 10.    \[Victim 1\] worked as a prostitute from November 2014 to early April 2015. \[…\] the accused requested that she sent him photographs and videos of her sexual engagements with her clients. \[Victim 1\] estimated that she sent the accused more than 20 photographs and less than 10 videos (including videos of herself having sexual intercourse with other men) during these six months. On the accused’s request, \[Victim 1\] would also send him her nude photographs. She did so as “Nurul Huda” told her that her job scope included pleasing the boss and/or pimp of the prostitution ring. \[…\] Sometime in April 2015, the accused contacted \[Victim 1\] using his email “**_XXX@hotmail.com_**” and found out that she had stopped prostitution. Sensing an opportunity, the accused posed as “**_Nurul Huda_**” and told \[Victim 1\] that “Hafiz” was disappointed that she had stopped prostitution without informing him. The accused told \[Victim 1\] that in order for her to exit the industry, \[Victim 1\] was to have a session with “Hafiz”. \[Victim 1\] agreed. During this session, the accused posed as “Hafiz”, the purported pimp, and \[Victim 1\] fellated the accused and had penile-anal intercourse with him.

> 12.    Thereafter, from April 2015 to May 2018, the accused used the email “XXX@hotmail.com” and sent a series of threatening and harassing emails to \[Victim 1\]. In these emails, he would send \[Victim 1\] her compromising photographs and threatened to post these photographs on the internet, let her family know that she was involved in prostitution or to approach \[Victim 1\]’s sister and get her involved in prostitution. He told \[Victim 1\] that if she did not want him to carry out these threats, she would have to carry out one of the following options:

>> a.    find new girls for him;

>> b.    record a video of herself having sexual intercourse with other men and send it to him;

>> c.    be a prostitute;

>> d.    send him nude photographs of herself daily; or

>> e.    be his mistress.

> 13.    By this time, the accused was aware that \[Victim 1\] was naïve. He wanted to capitalise on her naivety to satisfy his “lust, desire and need”. He knew that by putting \[Victim 1\] in fear, she would comply with his demands.

> 14.    \[Victim 1\] initially opted to find new girls for the accused. As she was unsuccessful in doing so, she then opted to be his mistress. The accused remained unsatisfied and she eventually sent him photographs of herself in underwear and photographs/videos of herself performing fellatio on other men. Notwithstanding, the accused continued to threaten her so as to obtain more of such photographs and videos.

### Facts relating to charges in \[3(12)\] – \[3(14)\]

> 62.    On 4 April 2018, \[Victim 3\] and \[Victim 4\] separately responded to the job advertisement. In his individual chats with \[Victim 3\] and \[Victim 4\] via Facebook messenger, he employed the modus operandi set out at paragraphs \[42\]-\[43\] and continued to impersonate as a female.

He also introduced \[Victim 2\] as his ex-PA. This was so as to resolve any doubts \[Victim 3\] and \[Victim 4\] may have about the job. Prior to creating the group chat, he told \[Victim 2\] that he had two personal assistants “under trial” and she was to be the overall in charge. \[Victim 2\] was to send her compromising photographs and videos to the group chat and to convince \[Victim 3\] and \[Victim 4\] to send him their obscene photographs and videos. \[Victim 2\] complied with his instructions.

> 66.    After seeing others do the same, \[Victim 4\] was convinced and became more active sending her compromising photographs and videos (in both her individual chat with the accused and in the group chat). \[…\]

### Facts relating to charges in \[3(15)\]

9       Finally, the charge in \[3(15)\] involves **Victim 5**. The Accused had admitted to the following facts relating to that charge:

> 74    On the 4 April 2018, \[Victim 5\] responded to the advertisement by contacting the accused via Facebook messenger. She told the accused that she wanted to find out more about the job. The accused then requested for her compromising photographs and videos as part of the “consultation”. He also sent two videos of \[Victim 3\] and \[Victim 4\] fingering themselves as examples of the type of videos \[Victim 5\] was to send to him.

> 75.    \[Victim 5\] expressed her discomfort to the accused. The accused then told her to join the “My PAs” group chat. He told her that the group chat consisted of his present and ex personal assistants and they can help to clarify her doubts. \[Victim 5\] then stopped responding to the accused.

10     The aggregate sentences sought by the parties are as follows:

## Key thrusts of the Defence submissions

11     Before dealing with the Accused’s sentences, I wish to briefly address two key points raised by the Defence. The first is the Defence’s submission that the degree of sexual exploitation in the Accused’s offences was minimal, the level of premeditation was low, and the offences were committed due to “a lapse of judgement” (“**Defence first point**”).[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1) The Defence’s second point is that weight should be given to the Accused’s early guilty plea, full cooperation with the police and “sincere remorse” in sentencing (“**Defence second point**”).[^2]

12     I reject these points as they are utterly devoid of merit:

> (a)     Cheating is a choice. The Defence first point ignores the undisputed fact that the Accused had carefully planned and executed his sex scams. In the case of Victim 1 for instance, he had exploited her trust when she confided in him about her financial straits by suggesting that she join a purported prostitution ring. After successfully baiting Victim 1, the Accused exploited her naivety by initially deceiving her – and later intimidating her – into (i) sending him sexual materials and (ii) engaging in sexual acts with him. For the other victims, the Accused had lured them into his scams with false promises of a high-paying job with good working conditions. When these victims expressed doubts about his promises and demands, the Accused did not stop his scams. Instead, he tried to overcome their doubts by coming up with more lies to earn their trust and confidence. The Accused even had the audacity to introduce his victims to one another via a group chat so that they would be assured that there were others vying for the same “PA job” that he was offering. The Accused carried out his scams over three and a half years. During this time, he tricked his victims into sending 174 pieces of sexual materials.[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3) Given all these, it is highly disingenuous for the Defence to submit that the degree of sexual exploitation in the Accused’s multiple offences as minimal, the level of premeditation as low, and the carefully planned and executed offences as having been committed due to “a lapse of judgement”. The Accused is clearly seeking to minimise – without any basis – his culpability for his offences. In so doing, he has demonstrated an obvious lack of remorse.

> (b)     As for the Defence second point, I am of the view that the Accused’s guilty plea and cooperation with the police carry very little weight in sentencing. It bears noting that the Accused’s exchanges with the victims, including the transmission of the sexual materials and his threats to Victim 1, were all conducted over social media platforms. In the circumstances, the Prosecution would have little difficulty in proving the charges against the Accused by relying on these exchanges.

## Cheating by personation

13     Having dealt with the key points of the Defence submissions, I now come to the sentencing of the Accused’s offences, beginning with those under s 419 of the Penal Code.

### Sentencing approach for sex scams punishable under s 417

14     In _Wong Tian Jun_, the High Court had laid down the following sentencing approach for sex scam offenders convicted under s 417.

> (a)     A sentencing framework based on a _harm – culpability matrix_ applies to a sex scam offender who claims trial: _Wong Tian Jun_ at \[38\], \[40\] and \[41\].

> (b)     The offence-specific sentencing factors that go towards _harm_ include (i) the nature of the sexual act, and (ii) the effect of the offence on the victim. If the victim develops a lasting medically established psychiatric condition, then this can be a significant aggravating factor: _Wong Tian Jun_ at \[42\], \[45\] and \[49(c)\]. The procuring of sex by cheating represents a “grievous and reprehensible intrusion of bodily integrity”: _Wong Tian Jun_ at \[3\] and \[39\]. Where an offender deceives a victim into allowing him to have penile-vaginal intercourse with her, it is arguable that he may have committed rape under s 375 of the Penal Code. This is because any consent that the victim may have given for the sexual intercourse will have been vitiated by the misconception of fact that the offender has perpetrated on her: _Wong Tian Jun_ at \[33\]. Thus, where the same conduct is charged under s 417, it should be approached as being at the high end of seriousness for cases under s 417: _Wong Tian Jun_ at \[36\].

> (c)     The offence-specific sentencing factors that go towards _culpability_ include (i) the level of premeditation and subterfuge involved in the offence, and (ii) whether the offender has exploited the vulnerability of the victim: _Wong Tian Jun_ at \[43\], \[49\] and \[52\]. Where the victim is deceived into sending sexual material, the offender’s response when asked to delete the material is a relevant sentencing consideration. For instance, if the offender demands sexual acts from the victim as a condition to deleting the material, this counts as being the very highest level of culpability: _Wong Tian Jun_ at \[43\].

> (d)      _Offender_\-specific factors are also relevant to sentencing. For instance, repeated offending is an aggravating factor: _Wong Tian Jun_ at \[52\]. There is no general rule that pleading guilty entitles an offender to a discount of one third off his sentence: _Wong Tian Jun_ at \[41\] and \[49(e)\].

15     In addition to the sentencing factors identified in _Wong Tian Jun_, I am of the view that the following can also affect the level of gravity of a sex scam:

> (a)      **_Harm_** **.** First, where an offender cheats his victim into providing sexual materials of herself, _the nature of these materials_ is relevant in assessing the level of harm caused by the offence. For instance, a video that shows the victim’s private parts or the victim performing a sexual act can cause greater harm to the victim in mind and reputation than a photograph that shows the victim in a lingerie. Second, _what the offender has done with the sexual material_ is also relevant in sentencing. For instance, one of the most harmful acts that an offender can do is to publish the material on the Internet.

> (b)      **_Culpability._** An offender’s culpability is also affected by – (i) the degree of his persistence in perpetrating the deception, including whether he has carried out the deception over a lengthy period, and (ii) whether the offender has committed the offence in a group or as part of a criminal syndicate.

### Wong Tian Jun matrix and s 419

16     I now come to the issue of whether the _Wong Tian Jun_ matrix is applicable to sex scam offenders convicted under _s 419_ of the Penal Code (instead of under s 417), and if so, how.

#### Sentencing uplift approach is appropriate

17     I start by noting that cheating by personation under s 419 is clearly a more serious (aggravated) offence than cheating under s 417. Under s 417, the maximum term of imprisonment is _three_ years. Section 419, on the other hand, provides for a term of imprisonment which may extend to _five_ years. What distinguishes s 419 from s 417 is the element of personation – this element is a requirement under s 419 but not under s 417.

18     Depending on various factors, courts have adopted different approaches to sentencing an aggravated offence: see _Sentencing Frameworks in Singapore_ (Academy Publishing, 2022) at \[4-47\] – \[4-58\]. In _Public Prosecutor vs Periam Rij s/o Mathyalakan_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGDC 245</span> (“**_Periam_**”) at \[11\] – \[14\], I had taken the view that the sentencing “uplift” approach used in _Ng Soon Kim v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] 3 SLR 1097</span> could similarly be adopted to determine an appropriate sentence for an aggravated cheating offence under s 419. I had come to this view because –

> 14 \[…\] the facts that are used to establish an offence under s 419 can also be used to establish an offence under s 417. Furthermore, the sentencing factors that are relevant to an offence under s 417 are also relevant to an offence under s 419. In my view, the extent of the uplift will depend on how the nature and circumstances of the personation have aggravated the offence of cheating. Considering the prescribed punishments in s 419 and s 417, the _maximum extent of the uplift_ will be two years’ imprisonment.

> \[emphasis in original text\]

19     In the present case, I see no reason to depart from my views above. I had drawn the parties’ attention to _Periam_ and invited them to make submissions on the appropriateness of applying the uplift approach to a s 419 offence involving a sex scam. They have not raised any issue with such an approach.

20     Accordingly, applying the uplift approach to a s 419 offence involving a sex scam –

> (a)     The first step is to determine what could be an appropriate starting point sentence under the _Wong Tian Jun_ matrix had the offender been charged under s 417.

> (b)     After determining this starting point sentence, the next step to determine what sentencing uplift, if any, ought to be applied given that the offender is convicted of an aggravated offence under s 419.

21     Regarding the second step, I had held in _Periam_ at \[19\] that given that the _act of personation_ is what distinguishes s 419 from s 417, it would necessarily follow that the key factor in assessing whether (and if so to what extent) a sentencing uplift is appropriate is the _nature_ of the personation in the offence. I had then gone on to hold that there were at least three situations where a sentencing uplift would be warranted where the conviction is under s 419 – namely, where the personation involves (a) an officer from a _public agency_, (b) an officer from a _financial institution_, and (c) the illegal use of _sensitive personal information_ of another person.

22     In deciding on the Accused’s sentence, I have found that there is a _fourth_ situation where a sentencing uplift is justified. This is (1) where the offender has _exploited the features of the Internet and/or an online platform_ to personate another person (whether real or fictitious), _and_ (2) such exploitation is an _integral_ part of the cheating by personation. This view is supported by case law, which establishes that the exploitation of the Internet/online platform to commit an offence can be an aggravating factor in at least two situations.

> (a)     First, where the pervasiveness and reach of the Internet/online platform allows an offender to perpetuate his crimes on a much wider scale. An example of this is _Public Prosecutor v Syamsul Hilal bin Ismail_ <span class="citation">\[2012\] 1 SLR 973</span>. In that case, the Respondent had pleaded guilty to, among others, 15 cheating charges under s 420 of the Penal Code. Another 60 cheating charges were taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing. The cheating offences related, _inter alia_, to a car rental scam and a loan scam. The Respondent had posted _online_ advertisements to perpetuate these scams. On the Prosecution’s appeal, the High Court enhanced the Respondent’s sentence. In so doing, the court made the following observations:

>> 36    … I accept that the use of the Internet is a relevant sentencing consideration in that there is a strong public interest to deter potential offenders **_from using that medium_** to reach a larger number of potential victims. …

>> …

>> 40    … Yong CJ held (at \[23\] of _Rupchand Bhojwani_) that the court’s stance against Internet abuse should not be applied _carte blanche_ whenever an Internet or computer resource is misused; rather, the court must look at the role of such misuse in the commission of the offence. …

>> 41    When the Respondent’s individual offences are viewed in isolation, the Internet misuse in this case **_might seem “peripheral” because they could have been committed even without the medium of the Internet (eg, by traditional print media_**, as the Senior District Judge noted at \[32\] of the GD). However, it becomes clear that Internet misuse was not merely “peripheral” in this case when one views the Respondent’s numerous offences in their totality. Indeed, the most significant aggravating circumstance in this case was **_the large number of offences committed, which was largely facilitated by the Respondent’s use of the Internet to effectively publicise his scams_**. As the Prosecution submitted, the geographical reach of his criminal enterprise was remarkable. The Respondent collected monies from victims of his car rental scam in car parks and void decks all over Singapore – from Pasir Ris, to Jurong West and to Woodlands. He might have been able to achieve a similar reach with an advertisement in the newspapers, but it was unlikely that that would have been as cost-effective. …

>> \[emphasis in bold added\]

> (b)     The second situation is where the anonymity provided by the Internet/online platform allows offenders to escape detection for their crimes: _Public Prosecutor v Wang Ziyi Able_ <span class="citation">\[2008\] 2 SLR(R) 1082</span> at \[31\]; _Lim Bee Ngan Karen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2015\] 4 SLR 1120</span> at \[66\] and \[67\]; _Public Prosecutor v Quek Chin Choon_ <span class="citation">\[2015\] 1 SLR 1169</span> at \[38\]. In this regard, the use of a false moniker on a social media platform is aggravating if it suggests an intent and/or attempt by the offender to conceal his identity: _AQW v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2015\] 4 SLR 150</span> at \[61\]. A deterrent sentence is necessary – especially for those who use social media platforms to gain, falsely, the trust of women and thereafter to sexually exploit them: _Tay Kim Kuan v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2001\] 2 SLR(R) 876</span> at \[18\].

23     To summarise, I am of the view that it is appropriate to apply a sentencing uplift if any of the four situations in \[21\] and \[22\] above are found to exist where an offender is convicted under s 419.

24     For completeness, I have also considered whether there is any issue of double counting between these four situations and the offence-specific sentencing factors for cheating set out in \[14\] and \[15\] above, especially premeditation and planning. In my view, the answer is no. The basis for treating the four situations as aggravating (and thus warranting a sentencing uplift) is the _nature of the personation_. This basis is conceptually distinct from the reason for treating premeditation and planning as aggravating – namely, that the offender has formed a _considered decision_ or _conscious choice_ to commit an offence: _Ng Kean Meng Terence v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] 2 SLR 449</span> at \[44(c)\]; _Mehra Radhika v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2015\] 1 SLR 96</span> at \[41\]. Finally, as will be evident later, there is no issue of double counting when I apply the uplift approach to sentencing the Accused’s s 419 offences.

### Sentence

#### Applying Step 1

25     Proceeding with Step 1 of the analysis, I assess the Accused’s _culpability_ to be _high_. Apart from what I have already stated in \[12(a)\] above, I wish to add that the Accused’s culpability is further aggravated by his opportunistic, manipulative, and predatory behaviour in luring his victims into his sex scams.

> (a)     For instance, when Victim 1 wanted to stop prostituting herself, the Accused took the opportunity to demand sexual acts from her as a condition for releasing her from his clutches. After Victim 1 reluctantly gave in to his demands,[\[note: 4\]](#Ftn_4) the Accused continued to exploit her thereafter – _with even more outrageous demands for more than a year_: see \[50(b)\] below. Driven to desperation, Victim 1 had no choice but to lodge a police report against the Accused in April 2017.[^5]

> (b)     The Accused had made Victim 2 to Victim 5 perform preposterous acts to secure the fake “PA job” that he was offering. For instance, as part of his “selection process”, the Accused had told his victims to send him photographs and videos of them smelling their stained G-strings. In the case of Victim 2, the Accused had even told her to insert her G-string into her vagina and to leave it inside for the day, to remove it only when she needed to urinate, and to reinsert the G-string into her vagina after she had urinated.

26     I assess the level of _harm_ in **DAC-922193-2021** (deceiving Victim 1 into engaging in fellatio _and_ penile-anal intercourse) and **DAC-922192-2021** (deceiving Victim 1 into performing fellatio) to be _high_.

> (a)     By deceiving Victim 1 into allowing him to have penile-anal intercourse and fellatio with her, the Accused arguably has committed sexual assault by penetration under s 376 of the Penal Code. This is because any consent that Victim 1 might have given for such sexual acts would have been vitiated by her misconception that the Accused was the ringleader of a prostitution ring and that giving in to his sexual demands was necessary for her to enter and leave prostitution. Following the approach taken in _Wong Tian Jun_, the deception in DAC-922193-2021 and DAC-922192-2021 – which led to Victim 1 performing sexual acts with him – should count as coming within the highest level of harm for an offence under s 417.

> (b)     Between the two offences, DAC-922193-2021 is clearly more harmful than DAC-922192-2021. The penile-anal penetration was clearly done without Victim 1’s consent. The Accused had used force to overcome her resistance to his demand for anal sex. According to the Statement of Facts which he had admitted:

>> 23    \[…\] the accused told \[Victim 1\] … that he wanted to have sexual intercourse with her. \[Victim 1\] rejected him. **_\[Victim 1\] then tried to get out of the car but the accused pulled her back into the car. He pushed her in between the two front seats._** At this point, \[Victim 1\] was facing down. She felt that if she had sexual intercourse with the accused, he would let her leave the purported prostitution ring. Thus, she stayed put. The accused then lifted up her dress and inserted his penis into her anus. \[Victim 1\] felt pain. No condom was used. The penile-anal intercourse lasted for about 15 minutes before the accused ejaculated on \[Victim 1’s\] back.

>> \[emphasis added\]

> (c)     Furthermore, I note that the above harrowing experience had left an indelible mark on Victim 1. In her victim impact statement, she stated that “\[w\]henever I passed (_sic_) by the place where he _raped_ me, I will have flash back of the incident and will be traumatised. During then, I was emotionally affected and will have nightmares” \[emphasis added\].

> (d)     Under the _Wong Tian Jun_ matrix, the sentencing range for _high culpability – high harm_ is 27 to 36 months’ imprisonment. Given the considerations highlighted above, I am of the view that the starting point sentence for DAC-922193-2021 and DAC-922192-2021 should be **three years’** imprisonment and **30 months’** imprisonment respectively.

27     I find that the offence in **DAC-92227-2021** comes within the _high culpability –_ **_low harm_** category of the _Wong Tian Jun_ matrix. This is because Victim 5 was _not_ deceived into transmitting any sexual material to the Accused. According to the matrix, the applicable sentencing range is nine to 18 months’ imprisonment. I understand the matrix to apply to a completed offence of cheating. Given that Victim 5 did not transmit any sexual material and in the absence of any evidence of specific harm caused to her, I am of the view that a suitable starting point sentence for DAC-92227-2021 is **three months’** imprisonment.

28     As for the rest of the proceeded s 419 charges, the relevant victims had been deceived into transmitting numerous sexual materials to the Accused. These included videos of the victims performing sexual acts. I find this to be an aggravating factor. In my view, these offences come within the _high culpability –_ **_medium harm_** category under the _Wong Tian Jun_ matrix which has a sentencing range of 18 to 27 months’ imprisonment. I assess that a starting point sentence of **22 months’** imprisonment is appropriate for each of these charges.

#### Applying Step 2

29     In my view, a **sentencing uplift of three months’** imprisonment ought to be applied to each of the Accused’s s 419 offences.

> (a)     The Accused had exploited the anonymity and reach provided by social media platforms (i) to scour for unsuspecting victims (\[4\] above), (ii) to earn their trust and thus lure them into his scams, and (iii) to enable him to receive sexual materials without having ever to expose himself.

> (b)     In the case of Victim 1, the Accused had in fact created three fake online profiles (“Irah Chocopie”, “Nurul Huda”, and “XXX@hotmail.com”) to mask his identity and to deceive her: see \[6\] above. But for the web of deceit so carefully and elaborately spun by the Accused online, Victim 1 would not have been duped into believing that “Hafiz” (the Accused) was the leader of a purported prostitution ring and to agree to perform sexual acts with him to start and stop working as a prostitute.

> (c)     To convince Victim 2 to Victim 5 that his bogus “job offer” was genuine, the Accused had used the convenience of the online platforms (i) to create of an “ex-PA” group chat and (ii) to share sexual materials that other “job applicants” had sent him as part of the application requirements.

> (d)     The anonymity afforded by the Internet had allowed the Accused to commit his offences with impunity for a substantial period. In this regard, I note that despite Victim 1 having lodged a police report against the Accused in April 2017,[\[note: 6\]](#Ftn_6) it was only some 13 months later (in May 2018)[^7] that the Police was able to establish his identity and arrest him.

30     Given the above and bearing in mind that the Accused had consented to 19 other similar charges being taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing, I impose the following sentences:

## Extortion

### Prescribed punishment

31     Moving on to the Accused’s extortion offence (DAC-922198-2021), the relevant provisions are as follows:

> **Extortion**

> 383 Whoever _intentionally_ puts any person in fear of _any harm_ to that person or to any other person, in body, mind, reputation or property, whether such harm is to be caused legally or illegally, and _thereby dishonestly induces_ the person so put in fear _to deliver_ to any person _any property_ or valuable security, or anything signed or sealed which may be converted into a valuable security, commits “extortion”.

> \[emphasis added\]

> **Punishment for extortion**

> 384\. Whoever commits extortion _shall be punished_ with imprisonment for a term of _not less than 2 years_ and _not more than 7 years_ and with _caning_.

> \[emphasis added\]

### Sentencing submissions

32     The parties’ sentencing submissions are as follows:

### Principal sentencing factor

33     Extortion attracts a mandatory minimum of two years’ imprisonment and caning. What makes the offence so serious is the _harm_ associated with an extortionate conduct – extortion preys on the victim’s fears and thereby compels him to act against his will (often to his detriment). The fact that harm is the key sentencing factor is also evident from the fact that Parliament has pegged the maximum prescribed punishment for extortion to the type of harm threatened:

<table align="left" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="Judg-2-tblr" frame="all" pgwide="1"><colgroup><col width="18.82%"><col width="42.18%"><col width="39%"></colgroup><tbody><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="middle"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Provision</b></p></td><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="middle"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Type of harm threatened</b></p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="middle"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Max. imprisonment term</b></p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="middle"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1">Section 384</p></td><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="middle"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1">Any harm in body, mind, reputation or property</p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="middle"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1">7 years</p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="middle"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1">Section 386</p></td><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="middle"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1">Death or grievous hurt</p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="middle"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1">10 years</p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="r" rowspan="1" valign="middle"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1">Section 388</p></td><td align="left" class="r" rowspan="1" valign="middle"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1">Accusation of an offence punishable with death or with imprisonment for life, or with imprisonment which may extend to 10 years</p></td><td align="left" class="" rowspan="1" valign="middle"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1">10 years</p></td></tr></tbody></table>

  
  

34     Given the mischief targeted by criminalising and punishing extortion, I am of the view that the harm in connection with an extortionate conduct ought to have the greatest influence on sentencing. There are three aspects to this harm:

> (a)     The _nature of the harm_ that an offender has threatened to inflict (“**threatened harm**”). The threatened harm can take _different forms_ – such as exposing or accusing a victim of having committed a wrongful act or crime. The threatened harm can also be of _different severity_. For instance, a threat to kill is clearly more serious than a threat to cause hurt: see \[33\] above.

> (b)     The _nature and value of the property extorted_ (“**intended harm**”). Clearly, a threat seeking to induce a victim to deliver a nude photograph of herself is more serious than one seeking to induce her to deliver an innocuous photograph of herself. Similarly, a threat that seeks to induce the victim to deliver a laptop is clearly more serious than one seeking to induce him to deliver a tablet.

> (c)     The _level of fear and other harm_ suffered by the victim due to the extortion (“**consequent harm**”). For instance, extortion that causes the victim to suffer a mental breakdown is more serious than one where the victim is unaffected by the threat.

35     In my view, a holistic assessment of the above three types of harm determines the level of gravity of an extortionate conduct.

> (a)     Where the harm is _low_, the mandatory minimum sentence of two years’ imprisonment (plus caning) will generally be appropriate.

> (b)     Where the harm is _moderate_, courts have imposed sentences of up to about four years’ imprisonment (plus caning): see \[40(d)\] below. Given that the mandatory minimum sentence is already relatively stiff, the level of harm should be significant before an extortionate conduct is characterised as moderate. This is subject to one caveat. The mandatory minimum sentence may still be appropriate – even though the harm is moderate – if there are strong mitigating factors in the offender’s favour: _Public Prosecutor v Chua Hock Leong_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] SGCA 32</span> at \[6\].

### Secondary offence-specific sentencing factors

36     The gravity of an extortionate conduct is also affected by the level of an offender’s culpability. Factors going towards this factor include the following:

> (a)     The offender’s _purpose_ for making the threat. Often, an offender commits extortion to obtain an advantage or gratification – whether in pecuniary or other forms. There can also be more malicious motives for committing extortion, such as to cause the victim to suffer personal ruin.

> (b)     The _way_ an offender conveys his threat. For instance, it is aggravating if an offender takes effort to maximise the victim’s fear or reinforce the seriousness of his threat by (i) repeating his threat (_Public Prosecutor v Ramasamy Ashwin_ <span class="citation">\[2012\] SGDC 38</span> (“**_Ramasamy Ashwin_**”) at \[15\]), (ii) displaying weapon to accompany his threat, (iii) causing property damage or hurt when making the threat, (iv) representing that he is a member of a secret society or criminal group, or (v) representing that he is a public officer who can exercise legal powers to the victim’s prejudice. Regarding the last example, it is particularly aggravating if the offender _personates_ a public officer to commit extortion. I echo the following observations in _Public Prosecutor v Kumaresan s/o Raman_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] SGDC 203</span> (“**_Kumaresan_**”):

>> 22 … It is trite that the personation of public officials undermines the trust vested by the normal citizenry on persons in authority. To commit extortion under such a guise is doubly tarnishing, as it creates the impression of corruption and abuse of power within government. It would also impede investigatory work if the authority and identity of law enforcement officials are called to question at every juncture.

> (c)     The offence is premediated and planned (_Ramasamy Ashwin_ at \[15\]) or is part of an organised criminal activity.

> (d)     The offender targets a vulnerable victim to commit extortion: _Kumaresan_; _Sarjit Singh Rapati v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2005\] 1 SLR(R) 638</span> (“**_Sarjit Singh Rapati_**”) at \[52\]; _Teo Hee Heng v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2000\] 2 SLR(R) 351</span>.

37     I am of the view that the factors in \[36\] above are the _secondary_ (and not the primary) determinants to sentencing an extortionate conduct. Let me demonstrate this with the following illustration.

> (a)      **_False police report example_**. In the first example, suppose an offender finds a _minor_ in a liquor control zone with a can of beer. He then _personates a police officer_ and threatens to make a false police report against the minor for breaching the Liquor Control (Supply and Consumption) Act (“**Liquor Control Act**”). The offender successfully extorts a $50-_bribe_ from the minor for not making the report.

> (b)      **_False information example_**. In the second example, suppose the victim is a food products manufacturer, and that the offender threatens to circulate false information on the Internet that the victim’s products are harmful to health if consumed. The offender thereby successfully extorts $500,000 in return for not circulating the false information.

> (c)      **_Relative gravity_**. The nature of harm and culpability for the two examples are set out below.

> Even though the false police report example has more culpability-enhancing factors than the false information example, it cannot be seriously doubted that the gravity of the offence in the former example is lower, and its offender is thus deserving of a lesser sentence, than the latter example.

### Offender-specific sentencing factors

38     Another set of factors that can affect sentencing relate to the offender. Examples include –

> (a)     Aggravating factors: (i) Offences taken into consideration; (ii) Relevant antecedents; (iii) Evident lack of remorse

> (b)     Mitigating factors: (i) Guilty plea; (ii) Voluntary restitution; (iii) Co-operation with authorities; (iii) Offender committed the offence due to a mental condition.

### Caning

39     Apart from the duration of the imprisonment term, the presence of aggravating factors can also affect the number of strokes imposed on an offender. This is especially so if a higher number of strokes is warranted for the purpose of retribution (e.g., because of the heinousness of the harm threatened or intended) and/or deterrence: _Sentencing Principles in Singapore_ (Academy Publishing, 2019) (“**_Sentencing Principles_**”) at \[29.005\] – \[29.012\].

### The precedents

40     The analysis in \[34\] to \[39\] is supported by the precedents:

> (a)     In _Public Prosecutor v Easudas Jason_ <span class="citation">\[2014\] SGDC 226</span>, the offender was convicted after a trial on three charges under s 384 read with s 109 of the Penal Code. He was sentenced to _two years’ and six months’ imprisonment and two strokes_ of the cane on each charge, with two of the imprisonment terms to run consecutively. (Total: Five years’ imprisonment and six strokes of the cane.) The offender, acting in _conspiracy_ with other persons, had posted a _false online advertisement_ purporting to offer escort and massage services by a girl. When the victims responded to the advertisement, the conspirators _pretended to be the father of the girl or a police officer_. They then extorted money from the victims by threatening to commence police investigations against them, or to publicise their case in the newspapers. The victims were thereby induced to transferred monies (total: $7,650) into a bank account provided by the conspirators. In sentencing, the court considered that the offence was sophisticated and that this was an aggravating factor.

> (b)     In _Ng Chee Bing v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2001\] SGDC 266</span>, the offender pleaded guilty to two charges of extortion under s 384 read with s 34 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 1985 Rev Ed). The offender and his accomplice had threatened bodily harm to the victim – a _13-year-old_ boy – and thereby induced the victim to deliver various items totalling about $360. The offender was sentenced to _three years’ imprisonment_ and _three strokes_ of the cane on each charge.

> (c)     In _Sarjit Singh Rapati_, the appellant and his accomplice were convicted after a trial on a charge under s 384 read with s 34 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 1985 Rev Ed). They had _assumed the guise of immigration officers_ to inspect the work permit of the F. They _wrongfully confined F to a motor vehicle_, then extorted money from the S by intentionally putting him in fear that they would keep F in wrongful confinement. The trial judge sentenced both offenders to _three years’ imprisonment_ and _six strokes of the cane_ for the extortion offence and four months’ imprisonment each for the wrongful confinement and false impersonation offences. The sentence for extortion was affirmed on appeal.

> (d)     In _Tan Kok Siong v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2002\] SGDC 309</span>, the offender pleaded guilty to two counts of extortion with common intention under s 384 read with s 34 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 1985 Rev Ed). Together with two accomplices, the offender had extorted a total of $240 as “_protection money_” from the victims – who were proprietors of makeshift handphone accessories stalls at a trade fair on two occasions. There is no evidence that the offender had any secret society links. Noting that sentences ranging from four to five years’ imprisonment had been passed along with caning in extortion cases involving the payment of “protection money”, the court imposed a deterrent sentence of _four years’ imprisonment_ and _six strokes_ of the cane on each of the two charges, with the sentences of imprisonment to run concurrently.

### Sentence

41     I now come to the sentence for the Accused’s extortion offence. I find that the sentence of two years’ imprisonment and three strokes of the cane proposed by the Defence does not commensurate with the _high level of harm_ in the Accused’s offence.

> (a)      **_Threatened harm_**. The Accused had threatened to publish Victim 1’s nude photographs on the Internet. This is a very serious threat. If the threat is carried out, it would be difficult (if not impossible) to remove Victim 1’s compromising photographs from the Internet completely. This will forever tarnish Victim 1’s reputation and cause her to suffer irreparable harm and distress.

> (b)      **_Intended harm_**. The Accused had wanted Victim 1 to subject herself to the indignity of performing sexual acts with other men just to fulfil his selfish sexual fantasies. Initially, he had wanted Victim 1 to send him a video of her engaging in sexual intercourse. After Victim 1 protested that this could not be done within the short timeframe that he had imposed, the Accused then demanded that she sends him, among others, a video of her sucking a man’s penis.

> (c)      **_Consequent harm_**. Suffice to note, it is evident from Victim 1’s victim impact statement that she had been traumatised by the Accused’s threats and actions.

42     I also find that the Defence’s proposed sentence does not consider the _high level of the Accused’s culpability_.

> (a)     The Accused had concealed his identity and exploited the anonymity afforded by online platforms when he conveyed his threats to Victim 1. I agree with the Prosecution that this anonymity would have heightened Victim 1’s alarm.

> (b)     Furthermore, the Accused seemed to derive perverted pleasure in tormenting Victim 1. He initially set a deadline of less than 24 hours for Victim 1 to send him videos of her having sexual intercourse with other men. When Victim 1 protested that the deadline was too short, the Accused did not relent. Instead, he emailed Victim 1’s compromising photographs to her to demonstrate that the seriousness of his threat. Victim 1 tried to placate the Accused by sending him photographs of her in bra and panty/G-string. When she asked for more time to get him the video that he had wanted while she continued to send him similar photographs, the Accused cynically replied that “_I hope you have a lot of different gstrings. I would love if you wear your sister’s panties_”.

43     I impose the following sentence:

### Ye Lin Myint

46     In _Ye Lin Myint_, the High Court set out a sentencing framework for the offence under s 507 read with s 506 of the Penal Code. The framework involved five steps.

47     The first step is to consider the offence-specific factors and classify the level of harm and the level of the offender’s culpability. The _harm factors_ included (a) the degree of alarm caused, or the extent to which the recipient was compelled to perform acts against his will or to refrain from exercising his rights; (b) public disquiet; and (c) physical harm occasioned by the threat. The _culpability factors_ included (a) the degree of planning and premeditation, (b) the offender’s motive, and (c), the degree to which the offender exploited his anonymity to cause alarm: _Ye Lin Myint_ at \[47\].

48     The second step is to identify the applicable indicative sentencing range according to the sentencing ranges set out in the matrix below.

![](data:image;base64,)

49     The third step is to identify the appropriate starting point within the indicative sentencing range. The fourth step involves adjusting the starting point to account for offender-specific factors. The final step involves making further adjustments to consider the totality principle.

### Sentence

50     I agree with the Prosecution that the Accused’s acts of criminal intimidation fall within the moderate harm – high culpability category of the _Ye Lin Myint_ matrix.

> (a)     Despite Victim 1 having given in to the Accused’s demand for fellatio and anal sex as a condition for promising not disturbing her anymore, he did not keep to his promise.

> (b)     Instead, preying on her deepest fears, the Accused had brazenly sent a series of contemptible emails to Victim 1 threatening to post her nude photographs on the Internet, to inform her family that she was involved in prostitution, and to get her sister involved in prostitution. In return for not executing his threats, the Accused demanded that Victim 1 (i) find new girls for him, (ii) record a video of herself having sexual intercourse with other men and send it to him, (iii) be a prostitute, (iv) send him nude photographs of herself daily, or (v) be his mistress.

> (c)     To impress on Victim 1 the seriousness of his threat, the Accused (i) had attached in his emails numerous nude photographs that he had previously deceived or pressured her into sending to him, and (ii) had cynically warned her that she would “be popular”. As rightly highlighted by the Prosecution[\[note: 8\]](#Ftn_8) –

>> … The accused invoked the prospect of harm to \[Victim 1’s\] loved ones, public humiliation and reputational damage. He was not satisfied merely with causing \[Victim 1\] alarm. Instead, he also hoped to extract unlawful gains from her.

>> … \[The Accused had\] wanted \[Victim 1\] to be acutely aware of her vulnerability … By sending her sexually explicit photographs of herself, he made certain that she was palpably conscious of the imbalance of power.

> (d)     The Accused was cruel towards Victim 1. When she asked him whether she was expected to entertain him for the rest of her life without getting married, he sarcastically replied that it was up to her whether she wanted to get married and that she could still entertain him after her marriage.

> (e)     As a result of the Accused’s threats, Victim 1 became “anxious, scared and frustrated”. It is understandable why she was distressed – the Accused had many sexual materials of her and had demonstrated that he had no qualms in ruining her reputation and life.

51     I note that the Accused had consented to three other similar charges being taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing. I impose the following sentences:

## Transmission of obscene materials

52     Finally, I come to the Accused’s offence under s 292(1)(a) read with s 109 of the Penal Code (DAC-92222-2021). For this offence, he had instigated Victim 2 to persuade Victim 3 and Victim 4 to transmit their obscene photographs and videos to him.

53     The Prosecution submitted for a short custodial sentence. The Defence did not make any submission for this offence.

54     I agree with the Prosecution that a short custodial sentence is appropriate. The Accused had hatched an elaborate ploy to deceive Victim 3 and Victim 4 into sending him their obscene materials. This ploy included the Accused (a) creating a group chat on Facebook messenger, (b) assuming a false identity in the group chat, and (c) deceiving Victim 2 into becoming part of his scam to overcome Victim 3 and Victim 4’s concerns about sending sexual materials to him. (See the Statement of Facts at \[65\]. This has been reproduced at \[8\] above.)

align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">6 months’ imprisonment</p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="r" colspan="2" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Aggregate</b></p></td><td align="left" class="" colspan="2" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>13 years’ imprisonment AND 5 strokes</b></p></td></tr></tbody></table>

  
  

57     In ordering five sentences to run consecutively, I have considered the totality principle: _Wong Tian Jun_ at \[62\] – \[68\]. I am mindful that the aggregate sentence of 13 years’ imprisonment is higher than what the Defence had submitted for (nine to 11 years’ imprisonment). In my view, the aggregate sentence is not manifestly excessive given the huge number of charges which have been taken into consideration and the overall gravity of the Accused’s offences. Neither is the aggregate sentence crushing. The Accused is 32 years old at the time of sentencing. With remission, he will be in his early 40s when he is released from prison and can still lead a productive life.

58     I am also mindful that the Accused’s aggregate sentence is longer than the aggregate sentence of eight years’ imprisonment in _Wong Tian Jun_. In my view, this is perfectly justifiable given that the Accused has committed (a) more offences, (b) of a more serious nature (under s 419, extortion and criminal intimidation punishable under s 507 of the Penal Code), and (c) over a longer period: see **Annex A**.

59     For completeness, I wish to state that the fact that the Accused was a police officer at the time of the offences did _not_ affect my sentencing decision. While it is tempting to take the view that the Accused should be punished more severely because he should have known better than to breach the law, the legal position is well-established – a deterrent sentence is warranted where the offender is a law enforcement officer _only if_ his offence is committed _in the course of his duty or under the colour of his office_. This is because an offence committed in such circumstances amounts to (a) an abuse of the trust and reliance reposed on the offender as a law enforcement officer, (b) an abuse of his authority, (c) a serious dereliction of his duty, (d) bring his organisation into disrepute, and/or (e) erode public confidence in the legitimate use of coercive powers vested in persons such as the offender. These considerations are not engaged if the offence is not connected with the offender’s duty as a law enforcement officer: _Sentencing Principles_ at \[16.157\] – \[16.169\]. In the present case, the Accused had committed the offences on his own frolic. These offences had not been committed _in the course of his duty or under the colour of his office_ as a police officer.
